d institutional records paint a vivid picture of a world in which both middle-class and working-class American Jewish women were consistently andpublicly engaged in all the major issues of their day and worked closely with their non-Jewish counterparts on behalf of activist causes.This extraordinarily well researched volume makes a unique contribution to the study of modern women's history, modern Jewish history, and the history of American social movements.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aJewish womenxPolitical activityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewish womenzUnited StatesxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aWomen and peacezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenxSuffragezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenzUnited StatesxSocial conditionsy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081474894740uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814748947.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814749463423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814749463/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK